<tag name="trans">
	<shortinfo> Layer transitions </shortinfo>
	<group> Layer operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="layer">
			<shortinfo> Target layer </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> "base" (default) or an integer greater than or equal to or message0 or message1 or message</format>
			<info>
				　Specify the target layer.<BR>
				　If you specify base, it will be the background layer.<BR>
				　Specifying an integer greater than or equal to 0 results in a foreground layer.<BR>
				　Specifying message0 or message1 is the message layer. If you simply specify message only, the message layer specified in the <ref tag="current">current</ref> tag is the target (No matter which message layer of the back page or the front page is the target, the transition is made from the back page to the front page.)<BR>
				　Normally, make the transition to base.<BR>
				　There are quite a few restrictions when transitioning to something other than base.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="children">
			<shortinfo> Whether to include child layers </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> true (default) or false </format>
			<info>
				　Specifies whether to include child layers in the transition. Specifying true includes child layers. If false is specified, child layers are not included.<BR>
				　Can be used only when layer=base is specified.<BR>
				　Child layers include the foreground layer and the message layer.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="time">
			<shortinfo> Transition time </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> Time (ms) </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the transition time as a numeric value.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="method">
			<shortinfo> Transition type </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> "universal" (default) or "scroll" or other </format>
			<info>
				　Specifies the type of transition.<BR>
				If "universal" is specified, a universal transition will be performed according to the rule, vague, and time attributes.<BR>
				If "crossfade" is specified, a simple crossfade is performed according to the time attribute.<BR>
				If "scroll" is specified, scroll transition is performed based on from and stay.<BR>
				　Some types of transitions are made available by plug-ins. In that case, you must specify the name of the transition in the method attribute, and you may need to specify another attribute for some transitions.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="rule">
			<shortinfo> Rule image </shortinfo>
			<required> Only when method=universal </required>
			<format> Rule image name </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the rule image used for the universal transition.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="vague">
			<shortinfo> Ambiguous area value </shortinfo>
			<required> Only when method=universal </required>
			<format> Ambiguous area value (0~) </format>
			<info>
				　Specifies the fuzzy region value that applies to universal transitions.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="from">
			<shortinfo> Scroll direction </shortinfo>
			<required> Only when method=scroll </required>
			<format> "left" or "top" or "right" or "bottom" </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the direction from which the image of the back page appears in the scroll transition. "left" = left, "top" = top, "right" = right, "bottom" = bottom
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="stay">
			<shortinfo> Whether the original image stays there </shortinfo>
			<required> Only when method=scroll </required>
			<format> "stayfore" or "stayback" or "nostay" (default) </format>
			<info>
				　In a scroll transition, specify if the image on the back page scrolls from outside while the image on the front page stays in place ("stayfore"),<BR>
				　or the image on the front page scrolls out from behind Whether the image on the page stays in place ("stayback"),<BR>
				　or the image on the front page and the image on the back page are linked and switch while moving ("nostay")
 			</info>
		</attrib>
	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Performs a transition on the specified layer.<BR>
		　The transition always occurs in the direction that the target layer on the back page is replaced with the target layer on the front page.<BR>
		　After the transition, the image, position, size, visible / invisible state of the target layer on the front page will be the same as the target layer on the back page.<BR>
		　Generally, the transition of method=universal is to copy the information of the front page to the back screen with the <ref tag="backlay">backlay</ref> tag, operate the layer with the <ref tag="image">image</ref> or <ref tag="layopt">layopt</ref> tag for the back page, and set this trans tag with layer=base children=true. And wait for the end of the transition in the <ref tag="wt">wt</ref> tag.<BR>
		　It may be useful to macroize this series of operations with <ref tag="macro">macro</ref> tags.<BR>
		　During a transition, characters cannot be displayed or may be slow. Also, since the status is basically "undefined," wait for the end of the transition before moving the position or changing the display / non-display.<BR>
		　Normally, transitions are made to the background layer, but you can make individual transitions to the foreground and message layers for special purposes. However, there is a restriction that the size of the layer on the back page / screen must be the same.<BR>
		　Unless it is used for a really special purpose (although I can't say for sure), specify base for layer.<BR>
		<BR>
		　This tag does not wait for the transition to end. Use <ref tag="wt">wt</ref> tags to wait for the transition to end.<BR>
	</remarks>
	<example>
		[backlay]<BR>
		[image storage=fg0 layer=0 page=back]<BR>
		[trans method=universal time=1500 rule=trans0 vague=64]<BR>
		[wt]<BR>
	</example>
</tag>

<tag name="stoptrans">
	<shortinfo> Stop layer transition </shortinfo>
	<group> Layer operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Force abort transitions started with <ref tag="trans">trans</ref> tags. Transitions for all layers stop.<BR>
		　The image will be completely switched.
	</remarks>
</tag>


<tag name="move">
	<shortinfo> Automatic layer movement </shortinfo>
	<group> Layer operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="layer">
			<shortinfo> Target layer </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> An integer greater than or equal to 0 or message0 or message1 or message </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the target layer.<BR>
				　Specifying an integer greater than or equal to 0 results in a foreground layer.<BR>
				　Specifying message0 or message1 will be the message layer. If only message is specified, the message layer of the current operation target specified by the <ref tag="current">current</ref> tag is targeted.<BR>
				　Do not specify a background layer.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="page">
			<shortinfo> page </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> "back" or "fore" </format>
			<info>
				　Specifies whether the layer specified by the layer attribute is the front (fore) screen or the back (back) screen. If omitted, it is assumed to be a table page.<BR>
				　However, if only layer=message is specified and this attribute is omitted, the message layer of the current operation target page will be selected.
			</info>
		</attrib>


		<attrib name="spline">
			<shortinfo> Spline interpolation </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> true or false (default) </format>
			<info>
				　If true is specified, the layer will move on the line interpolated by the B-spline at the position specified by the path attribute.<BR>
				　If false is specified, the layer moves on the line that is linearly interpolated at the position specified by the path attribute.<BR>
				　If true is specified, specify at least 2 points for path.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="time">
			<shortinfo> Time to pass one point </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> Time (ms) </format>
			<info>
				　Specifies the time required for the layer to move points from the point specified by path.<BR>
				　Therefore, it takes time to move the number of sections between passing points x the value of this attribute.<BR>
				　However, if a value other than 0 is specified for the accel attribute, the time required to pass one point will change (the time required for the entire movement will be the number of sections to pass x the value of this attribute).
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="delay">
			<shortinfo> Time to start operation </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Time (ms) </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the time, in ms, before the automatic movement of the layer starts.<BR>
				　If omitted, it is assumed to be 0.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="path">
			<shortinfo> Movement position </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> "(x1,y1,opacity1) (x2,y2,opacity2) ..." </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the movement position.<BR>
				　The movement position is specified by x (left end position of layer), y (top end position of layer), and opacity (layer density), each separated by a comma, blank, or ().<BR>
				　The layer moves between them by spline interpolation or linear interpolation.<BR>
				　For opacity, specify the display density of the layer. The density of the layer also changes continuously as you move from point to point. If you want the density of the layer to change suddenly rather than continuously, specify a value obtained by adding 256 to the density.<BR>
				　To change only the display density without moving the layer, specify the same position for all layer positions.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="accel">
			<shortinfo> Whether to make an acceleration movement </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Number less than -1 or 0 (default) or number greater than 1 </format>
			<info>
				　Specify whether or not to make acceleration movement.<BR>
				　If you specify 0, the movement process proceeds at a fixed rate from the beginning to the end (passes each passing point at equal intervals). If omitted, 0 is assumed.<BR>
				　If you specify a number less than -1, it is initially fast and gradually slows down.<BR>
				　If you specify a number greater than 1, it is slow at first and gradually faster.<BR>
				　You can also specify a real number.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Causes the specified layer to move automatically.<BR>
		　The layer starts from the current position and display density, moves and changes the display density based on the position and display density specified by path. Since movement starts from the current position and display density, it is not necessary to specify the position and display density of the first layer in the first position / density of the path attribute. (In other words, the first position and display density must be specified with <ref tag="layopt">layopt</ref> tags, etc.).<BR>
		　You can execute the move tag asynchronously for multiple layers.<BR>
		　This tag does not wait for the automatic movement of the layer to end. Please specify an <ref tag="wm">wm</ref> tag to wait.<BR>
		　If you load a screen larger than the screen into the foreground layer and use this tag to move it, you can get the scrolling effect. Diagonal scrolling is also possible.<BR>
		　During automatic movement, character drawing on the message layer may not be possible or character drawing may be slow.<BR>
		　Automatic movement is interrupted by clicking the mouse. To avoid interruptions, ban click skipping with <ref tag="clickskip">clickskip</ref> tags.
	</remarks>
	<example>
[image storage=s1 layer=0 page=fore visible=true left=0 top=480 opacity=0]<BR>
[image storage=s2 layer=1 page=fore visible=true left=320 top=240 opacity=0]<BR>
[move time=4000 path="(0,240,255) (0,0,255) (0,-240,255) (0,-480,0)" layer=0]<BR>
[move time=4000 path="(320,240,0) (320,240,511) (320,240,0) (320, 240,0)" layer=1]<BR>
[wm][wm]
	</example>
</tag>


<tag name="stopmove">
	<shortinfo> Stop automatic layer movement </shortinfo>
	<group> Layer operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Forcibly stop the automatic movement started by the <ref tag="move">move</ref> tag. Automatic movement of all layers stops.<BR>
		　The image moves to the final position and has the final display density.
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="laycount">
	<shortinfo> Changing the number of layers </shortinfo>
	<group> Layer operation </group>

	<attribs>
		<attrib name="layers">
			<shortinfo> Number of foreground layers </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> 0 or a positive integer </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the number of foreground layers.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="messages">
			<shortinfo> Number of message layers </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Positive integer </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the number of message layers.<BR>
				　0 cannot be specified.
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>
	
	<remarks>
		　Change the number of foreground or message layers. If you omit any attribute, the setting will not be changed.<BR>
		　There is no limit on the number of layers, but it may be limited by the OS and memory of the execution environment.<BR>
		　The number of layers should be kept to a minimum. Once you have a lot of layers and you're done with them, it's best to get them back to the bare minimum.<BR>
	</remarks>
</tag>


<tag name="ct">
	<shortinfo> Reset message layer </shortinfo>
	<group> Message operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Reset the message layer。<BR>
		　All message layer characters are deleted, and the message layer to be operated is specified in message0 on the front page.<BR>
		　The attributes of the characters specified by the <ref tag="font">font</ref> tag and the style specified by the <ref tag="style">style</ref> tag all return to the standard state. However, attributes specified in <ref tag="position">position</ref> and <ref tag="layopt">layopt</ref> tags are inherited.<BR>
		　<ref tag="er">er</ref> tags, on the other hand, simply erase characters on the current message layer of interest and reset character and style attributes to their default state.<BR>
		　This ct tag or <ref tag="cm">cm</ref> tag should follow the label of the form "*label name|heading name". (The execution starts from the label when the bookmark is loaded, but the characters on the message layer are always cleared when the bookmark is loaded.)<BR>
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="cm">
	<shortinfo> Clear all message layers </shortinfo>
	<group> Message operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Clear all message layers.<BR>
		　All message layer characters are deleted, but the message layer to be operated is not specified in message0 of the front page like <ref tag="ct">ct</ref> tag. After executing this tag, the operation target layer is the same.<BR>
		　The attributes of the characters specified by the <ref tag="font">font</ref> tag and the style specified by the <ref tag="style">style</ref> tag all return to the standard state. However, attributes specified in <ref tag="position">position</ref> and <ref tag="layopt">layopt</ref> tags are inherited.<BR>
		　This cm tag or <ref tag="ct">ct</ref> tag should follow the label in the format "*label name|heading name". (The execution starts from the label when the bookmark is loaded, but the characters on the message layer are always cleared when the bookmark is loaded.)<BR>
	</remarks>
</tag>



<tag name="delay">
	<shortinfo> Setting the display speed of characters </shortinfo>
	<group> Message operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="speed">
			<shortinfo> Character weight </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> "nowait" or "user" or weight value (in ms) </format>
			<info>
				　If "nowait" is specified, characters are displayed at once without weighting the characters. If "user" is specified, the speed specified by the user in [System | Character Speed] will be used (default). If you specify a weight value, characters are displayed at the rate of one character per the time indicated by the value.<BR>
				　The character display speed is the same for all message layers.
			</info>
		</attrib>
	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Specify the display speed of characters.<BR>
		　You can also use <ref tag="nowait">nowait</ref> tags to make the text display no-wait.
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="nowait">
	<shortinfo> Character display no wait </shortinfo>
	<group> Message operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Set the character display speed to no wait.<BR>
		　This tag remembers the last character display speed before setting it to no wait. You can use <ref tag="endnowait">endnowait</ref> tags to return to this memorized character display speed.<BR>
		　Do not write a savable label between this tag and the endnowait tag.
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="endnowait">
	<shortinfo> Character display no wait (end) </shortinfo>
	<group> Message operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Returns the display speed of the character to the character display speed immediately before the <ref tag="nowait">nowait</ref> tag made no-wait.<BR>
	</remarks>
</tag>



<tag name="emb">
	<shortinfo> Embedding expression evaluation results </shortinfo>
	<group> Variable / TJS operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="exp">
			<shortinfo> TJS expression </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> TJS expression </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the TJS expression to evaluate. The result of the expression evaluated here replaces this emb tag.
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Evaluates (executes) the expression indicated by exp and embeds the result.<BR>
		　Use this when you want to display variables in a scenario.<BR>
		　Usually, replace with the contents of the variable assigned by the <ref tag="eval">eval</ref> tag.
	</remarks>
	<example>
		[eval exp="f.value1='variable value'"]<BR>
		<BR>
		If you write it somewhere and write <BR>
		<BR>
		[emb exp="f.value1"]<BR>
		<BR>
		, this emb tag will be replaced with the variable value.<BR>
	</example>
</tag>



<tag name="endlink">
	<shortinfo> Hyperlink (end) </shortinfo>
	<group> Label jump operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Marks the end of a hyperlink started with an <ref tag="link">link</ref> tag.
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="endmacro">
	<group> Macro operation </group>
	<shortinfo> Macro description (end) </shortinfo>

	<remarks>
		　Indicates the end of the macro that started the description with the <ref tag="macro">macro</ref> tag.
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="endscript">
	<group> Variable / TJS operation </group>
	<shortinfo> Writing TJS script (end) </shortinfo>

	<remarks>
		　Indicates the end of the script described in [<ref tag="iscript">iscript</ref>].<BR>
		Only this tag can be written on the line with this tag (even the \ symbol at the end of the line is not allowed).
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="erasemacro">
	<shortinfo> Clear macro </shortinfo>
	<group> Macro operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="name">
			<shortinfo> Tag name </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> Tag name </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the tag to be deleted. Only tags defined as macros can be deleted.
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Delete the macro described by the <ref tag="macro">macro</ref> tag.
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="indent">
	<shortinfo> Set indent </shortinfo>
	<group> Message operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Set the left indent (head indent for vertical writing) at the position of this tag. You can use it as a speaker indent. To remove indentation, use a <ref tag="endindent">endindent</ref> tag before the line break.
	</remarks>
	<example>
		[[Anpan] [indent] You can use it as a speaker indent. [endindent]
	</example>
</tag>

<tag name="endindent">
	<shortinfo> Remove indent </shortinfo>
	<group> Message operation </group>
	<remarks>
		　Remove the indent set by the <ref tag="indent">indent</ref> tag. Usually, it is written before a line feed.
	</remarks>
</tag>

<tag name="eval">
	<shortinfo> Expression evaluation </shortinfo>
	<group> Variable / TJS operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="exp">
			<shortinfo> TJS expression </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> TJS expression </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the TJS expression to evaluate.
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Evaluates the expression indicated by exp. Usually used to assign values to variables.<BR>
		　Because exp can be any TJS expression, any expression that is valid for TJS can be evaluated.<BR>
	</remarks>
	<example>
		[eval exp="f.test=500"]<BR>
		;↑Assigning a numerical value to the game variable test<BR>
		[eval exp="f.test2='String'"]<BR>
		;↑Assigning a character string to game variable test2<BR>
		[eval exp="sf.test=400"]<BR>
		;↑Assigning a numerical value to the system variable test<BR>
		[eval exp="f.test2=f.test*3"]<BR>
		;↑Game variable test2 is substituted with 3 times the value of game variable test<BR>
	</example>
</tag>

<tag name="trace">
	<shortinfo> Output value to console </shortinfo>
	<group> Variable / TJS operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="exp">
			<shortinfo> TJS expression </shortinfo>
			<required> yes </required>
			<format> TJS expression </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the TJS expression to evaluate.
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Evaluates the expression represented by exp and prints the result to the console.<BR>
		　The console is displayed with Shift+F4 and can also be logged to a file by setting logMode in Config.tjs.<BR>
	</remarks>
	<example>
		[trace exp="f.test"]<BR>
		; ↑ Output the contents of the game variable test to the console<BR>
		; The following is displayed on the console (example)<BR>
		;  6:45:34 ▼[trace] expression="f.test"  type of result=Number  result=500<BR>
	</example>
</tag>


<tag name="font">
	<shortinfo> Character attribute setting </shortinfo>
	<group> Message operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="size">
			<shortinfo> font size </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Character size (pixel unit) or "default"</format>
			<info>
				　Specify the font size in pixel units.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="face">
			<shortinfo> Font name </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Font name or "default" or "user" </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the font name.<BR>
				　Font names cannot be ambiguous. Please specify space, half-width / full-width exactly.<BR>
				　You can specify multiple font names separated by commas. In this case, if there is a font written at the beginning, it will be selected with priority.<BR>
				　Example: face="Noto Sans,Arial"<BR>
				　The font for vertical writing is automatically set, so there is no need to put the @ mark at the beginning of the font name.
				　If "user" is specified, it will be the font selected by the user in the menu [Character display | Font].
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="color">
			<shortinfo> Letter color </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> 0xRRGGBB format or "default"  </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the font color in 0xRRGGBB format.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="italic">
			<shortinfo> Whether italic </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> true or false or "default" </format>
			<info>
				　Specifies whether characters are italic. Specify true to make italic.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="rubysize">
			<shortinfo> Ruby size </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Ruby text size (pixels) or "default" </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the size of ruby (Furigana) characters in pixel units.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="rubyoffset">
			<shortinfo> Ruby display position </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Ruby display offset (pixel unit) or "default" </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the display offset of ruby in pixel units. If you specify a negative number, it will be displayed closer to the text.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="shadow">
			<shortinfo> Whether to show shadows </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> true or false or "default" </format>
			<info>
			　Specify whether to add shadow to characters. If true is specified, the shadow will be cast.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="edge">
			<shortinfo> Whether to use border characters </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> true or false or "default" </format>
			<info>
			　Specify whether to use a blank character (border character). If true is specified, it becomes a bag character.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="edgecolor">
			<shortinfo> Bag character bag color </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> 0xRRGGBB format or "default" </format>
			<info>
			　Specifies the color of the text bag in the format 0xRRGGBB.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="shadowcolor">
			<shortinfo> Shadow color </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> 0xRRGGBB format or "default" </format>
			<info>
			　Specifies the color of the shadow in 0xRRGGBB format.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="bold">
			<shortinfo> Bold </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> true or false or "default" </format>
			<info>
			　Specify whether to make the characters bold. If true is specified, bold characters will be used.<BR>
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Specifies various attributes of the character.<BR>
		　These attributes can be set individually for each message layer.<BR>
		　If both attributes are omitted, the previous state is inherited. If default is specified, it will return to the default value specified in Config.tjs.<BR>
		　If edge and shadow are set to true at the same time, only the envelope character is valid and the shadow is ignored.<BR>
		　These attributes return to the default values specified in Config.tjs and in the <ref tag="deffont">deffont</ref> tag when the <ref tag="resetfont">resetfont</ref> tag or <ref tag="ct">ct</ref> <ref tag="cm">cm</ref> <ref tag="er">er</ref> tag is executed.
	</remarks>
</tag>

