				　100 is the upper limit. Only volume control is supported (amplification is not possible due to the characteristics of the sound source).
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Fade the sound effect to the specified volume.<BR>
		　This tag does not wait for the end of the fade.
		Use <ref tag="wf">wf</ref> tags to wait.<BR>
	</remarks>
</tag>


<tag name="seopt">
	<shortinfo> Sound effect settings </shortinfo>
	<group> Sound effects / BGM / Video operation </group>
	<attribs>
		<attrib name="buf">
			<shortinfo> Sound effect buffer number </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Sound effect buffer number (0 (default) ~) </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the buffer whose settings you want to change.<BR>
				　If omitted, it is assumed to be 0.
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="volume">
			<shortinfo> Volume </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Volume% (0-100) </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the volume of the sound effect in%. 100% for the default KAG. If omitted, the volume will not change.<BR>
				　100 is the upper limit. Only volume control is supported (amplification is not possible due to the characteristics of the sound source).
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="gvolume">
			<shortinfo> Global volume </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Volume% (0-100) </format>
			<info>
				　Specifies the global volume of the sound effect in %. 100% for the default KAG. If omitted, the volume will not change.<BR>
				　Global volume is another thing that can control the volume of the buffer, apart from the normal volume specified by the volume attribute. The actual playback volume is the volume obtained by multiplying the normal volume and the global volume (for example, if volume=50 and gvolume=75, 50 (%) * 75 (%) = 37.5 (%))<BR>
				　The global volume is recorded in a system variable for each sound effect buffer, and is carried over the next time it is started (it is not stored in each bookmark).
			</info>
		</attrib>

		<attrib name="pan">
			<shortinfo> Pan </shortinfo>
			<required> no </required>
			<format> Pan (-100~0~100) </format>
			<info>
				　Specify the pan (left and right sound image positions).<BR>
				　-100 is perfect left, 0 is center, and 100 is perfect right.
			</info>
		</attrib>

	</attribs>

	<remarks>
		　Change settings for individual buffers of sound effects.<BR>
	</remarks>
</tag>


